question: the kinked demand curve in oligopoly is used to explain
response_text: In an oligopoly market, companies typically keep prices steady and use methods other than price to compete, as seen in the kinked demand curve model. If one company raises prices, others are unlikely to follow suit to maintain their market share. Conversely, if one company lowers prices, others are likely to do the same to prevent losing customers. This results in stable prices and competition centered on advertising, product options, and customer service.
